# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Units
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:unit-3002
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Citizenship - what's it all about?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils consider what citizenship is all about, they will explore what knowledge and skills they need to develop to become active citizens."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit provides an introduction to some of the key citizenship concepts that pupils will study throughout their citizenship journey. Building on knowledge from the primary curriculum, students consider their existing knowledge on concepts such as democracy, rights and responsibilities and active citizenship and explore how this knowledge will be expanded through studying citizenship.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know to listen to the opinions of others.
Pupils are familiar with British values, such as democracy and liberty.
Pupils know how Citizenship is different to other subjects.""" ;
  curric:id "3002"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.354284Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-rights-justice-and-the-law ,
    oakcurric:thread-active-citizenship-making-a-positive-difference .

oakcurric:unit-3478
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How can we make a difference in our communities?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils examine what community means and the role it plays at their school. They explore what charities and NGOs do in their community and identify how they can become active citizens."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Building on their learning of how they can make a positive difference in their communities this unit continues to develop pupils’ knowledge of social issues and the role citizens and organisations have in creating positive change. This knowledge helps pupils to understand how citizens can work together to improve communities and wider society and how they can make their voice heard by those in positions of power.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know they belong to various groups and communities, such as family and school.
Pupils recognise the role of voluntary, community and pressure groups.
Pupils know there are different kinds of responsibilities, rights and duties at home, at school and in the community, and that these can sometimes conflict with each other.""" ;
  curric:id "3478"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.360509Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-active-citizenship-making-a-positive-difference .

oakcurric:unit-3204
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What is crime?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils consider what crime is, what causes criminal behaviour and how communities can help prevent crime. They also explore whether youth crime is really as serious as the media portrays."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn about what crime is because they are beginning to understand the rules and laws that help govern society. Understanding what constitutes a crime and its impact is crucial for their sense of justice and responsibility. This knowledge helps them recognize the importance of law, the consequences of crime, and the role of the justice system in protecting citizens including young people and maintaining order.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements "[TO BE ADDED]" ;
  curric:id "3204"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.361025Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-rights-justice-and-the-law .

oakcurric:unit-3029
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What rights should all children have?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces what rights we are all entitled to and how citizens can protect their rights. Pupils look in more depth at the right to health and the right to accurate information."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn about the rights all children should have because they are developing a sense of justice and  equity. Understanding children's rights is crucial for their awareness of global issues. This knowledge helps them recognize the importance of rights, advocate for themselves and others, and foster a fair and compassionate outlook as they develop as informed and responsible citizens.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know how to recognise what they like and dislike, what is fair and unfair, and what is right and wrong.
Pupils know that there are different kinds of responsibilities, rights and duties at home, at school and in the community, and that these can sometimes conflict with each other.""" ;
  curric:id "3029"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.363174Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-rights-justice-and-the-law .

oakcurric:unit-3203
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How does local democracy work?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit explores the difference between local and national government. Pupils consider how governments are elected, the role of local councils and the key people within them."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn about the differences between local and national government because they are starting to grasp how the political system works and impacts their lives. Understanding these differences is crucial for their civic awareness and participation in democracy. This knowledge helps them recognize the distinct roles and responsibilities of each level of government, fostering informed and active citizenship as they begin to engage with politcal and social ideas affecting communities and broader society.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know that they belong to various groups and communities, such as family and school.
Pupils know about participation in decision making. E.g. school councils.""" ;
  curric:id "3203"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.364212Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-politics-parliament-and-government .

oakcurric:unit-3368
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Are people treated equally in UK society?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils examine what discrimination is and how the law protects people against it, and consider what we can do to create a fairer society and how the UK has progressed in terms of equality."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Building on their understanding of rights and communities from Year 7 and 8, pupils in Year 9 learn about whether people are treated equally in UK society as they deepen their awareness of social justice, inclusion and equity. This knowledge helps them recognize discrimination including different racism, appreciate and value diversity, and advocate for a fairer society.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know about the importance of the law.
Pupils know about the difference between criminal and civil law.""" ;
  curric:id "3368"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.366087Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-rights-justice-and-the-law .

oakcurric:unit-3355
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How does the political system work in the UK?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils learn about the roles of government and parliament and how they are organised. They explore how elections work and what the role of political parties and MPs are."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn about how the political system works in the UK as they build their awareness of democracy and government. Understanding the structure and function of the UK political system is crucial for their development as informed citizens. This knowledge helps them grasp how political decisions are made within parliamentary democracy, the checks and balances within different branches of government, and the importance of citizen participation in elections and democracy.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know about voting and registering to vote.
Pupils know about government, such as local government.
Pupils know the difference between local and national government.""" ;
  curric:id "3355"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.374112Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-politics-parliament-and-government .

oakcurric:unit-3364
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What can we do about global problems?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Using a range of case studies from human rights to fracking and climate action, pupils consider how they can take responsible action to tackle some of the challenges currently facing society."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn about global problems and challenges as they develop a broader awareness of the world. Understanding complex issues that interconnect people and the planet such as climate change, poverty and inequality is crucial for fostering a sense of shared responsibility. This knowledge empowers them as they consider the actions that governments and those in power can take.  Alongside this they consider our own choices and decisions, and learn how they can be part of positive change, promoting a sense of collaboration, responsibility and global citizenship.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know about the role of NGOs, pressure groups and charities.
Pupils know about different ways active citizens can bring about change.""" ;
  curric:id "3364"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.375157Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-uk-and-the-wider-world .

oakcurric:unit-3369
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Why do people move around the world?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils consider why people migrate, the impact it has on communities, whether migration should be controlled and what support is available to migrants."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn about the different reasons why people move around the world as they develop a global perspective and understanding of migration. Building on earlier lessons about communities and global issues, understanding the complexity of migration is crucial for their awareness of diversity and change in communities and society. This knowledge helps them understand the economic, evironmental, social, and political factors driving migration, the complexities of migration globally as well as its impact on societies and the value of human rights and community cohesion.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know about human rights.
Pupils know about global challenges, such as climate change.""" ;
  curric:id "3369"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.375671Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-uk-and-the-wider-world .

oakcurric:unit-3004
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What are our identities and our communities?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces pupils to the concepts of identities and communities and how these change over time and contexts."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn about their identities and communities because they are beginning to understand the world around them. Understanding identities and community and diverse perspectives is crucial as their sense of belonging develops. This knowledge helps them appreciate how identities and communities change over time and helps to build a strong sense of interconnection and community.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know that their actions affect themselves and others, to care about other people's feelings and to try to see things from their points of view.
Pupils know to recognise and challenge stereotypes.
Pupils know the differences and similarities between people arise from a number of factors, including cultural, ethnic, racial and religious diversity, gender and disability.
Pupils appreciate the range of national, regional, religious and ethnic identities in the United Kingdom.""" ;
  curric:id "3004"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.382535Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-identities-and-communities .

oakcurric:unit-3358
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How does the media affect us?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit students explore the roles and responsibilities of the media and the important role it plays within society."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn about how the media affects us as they are increasingly exposed to various media and information sources. Understanding media influence, bias, and the importance of truth is crucial for developing critical thinking skills. This knowledge helps them discern reliable information, recognize bias, and understand the media's role in informing and shaping public opinion and holding those in power to account.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know about different sources of the news.
Pupils know that for most people the internet is an integral part of life and has many benefits.
Pupils know how to be a discerning consumer of information online including understanding that information""" ;
  curric:id "3358"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.392043Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-role-of-media-and-digital-democracy .

oakcurric:unit-3362
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How can citizens bring about change?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore the different ways citizens can take action and what role this plays in democracy."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn about the role of citizens and groups in shaping and improving communities. Pupils build on their foundational knowledge of democracy, rights and equity as they explore different methods of democratic participation and influencing change.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the term democracy.
Pupils understand precious liberties.
Pupils recognise the role of voluntary, community and pressure groups.""" ;
  curric:id "3362"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.394636Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-active-citizenship-making-a-positive-difference .

oakcurric:unit-3371
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Can digital democracy increase political participation?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils consider what a digital citizen is and how the digital world can be used to increase political engagement, examining cases of how digital democracy has worked across the globe."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Exploring digital democracy now helps pupils understand how digital tools can enhance political participation and engagement. This unit is timely as it prepares pupils to navigate rights related issues, and contribute to the evolving digital political landscape, empowering them to be informed and active citizens. By learning these concepts early, pupils can effectively participate in democratic processes, making this education relevant and impactful.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know what democracy is, and about the basic institutions that support it locally and nationally.
Pupils know that our lives increasingly involve being online.""" ;
  curric:id "3371"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.396155Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-role-of-media-and-digital-democracy .

oakcurric:unit-3363
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Why was the struggle for the vote important today?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils analyse how political rights have changed over time considering important campaigns such as the fight for female suffrage. They examine why voting matters and consider what role they can have in democracy prior to being eligible to vote."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn about the struggle for the vote because it is essential to understand the foundations of modern democracy, equality and representation. Understanding the historical context highlights the value of democracy and how it develop and changes over time. This knowledge helps them appreciate the significance of voting rights, active citizenship and change, and fosters an awareness of the importance to pursue equity.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know the meaning of the term democracy.
Pupils know about methods of participation in a democracy, such as voting.
Pupils know about types of elections, such as local elections.""" ;
  curric:id "3363"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.397164Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-rights-justice-and-the-law .

oakcurric:unit-3366
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How is the UK governed?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils explore the difference between local, regional and national governance and compare the political systems in the UK and US."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Building on their knowledge from Year 7 and 8 about the political system and the law, pupils in Year 9 learn about how the UK is governed as they develop political literacy. Understanding the structure of the UK government, including the roles of Parliament, the Prime Minister, and the judiciary, is crucial for their development as informed citizens. This knowledge helps them grasp how laws are made, how government functions, and the importance of democratic participation, preparing them for active and engaged citizenship.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know the difference between government and parliament.
Pupils know how elections work.
Pupils know about the role of political parties.""" ;
  curric:id "3366"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.398290Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-politics-parliament-and-government .

oakcurric:unit-3360
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "What is the law and how is it changed?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils explore what the law is and how criminal and civil laws are made. They examine what role citizens can have in changing the law and consider how the justice system should apply to young people."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils learn about what the law is and how it is changed because they are beginning to understand the structure of society and their role within it. Understanding the legal system and the process of lawmaking is crucial for their development as informed citizens. This knowledge helps them grasp the importance of laws, how they evolve to reflect societal values, and how individuals and groups can influence legal change, preparing them for active participation in their communities.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know why and how rules and laws are made and enforced.
Pupils know why different rules are needed in different situations and how to take part in making and changing rules.""" ;
  curric:id "3360"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.454734Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-rights-justice-and-the-law .

oakcurric:unit-3370
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How can we manage money well?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils explore how to look after their money considering the implications of borrowing, how they can keep track of their money, what saving options are available to them and what their rights are as a consumer."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils are becoming increasingly indepdent and will be considering future financial responsibilities. Learning to manage money now equips them with essential knolwledge and skills in relation to budgeting, saving, and making informed financial decisions in the future. They begin to connect personal financial choices and decisions with the understanding the economy, resources and their role in society as consumers, taxpayers and savers.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know that money comes from different sources and can be used for different purposes.
Pupils know to look after their money and realise that future wants and needs may be met through saving.""" ;
  curric:id "3370"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.482819Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-finance-and-the-economy .

oakcurric:unit-3372
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "How can young people play an active role in democracy?"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils consider what role they can play in their communities from school to local and national democracy."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Learning how young people can play an active role in democracy equips pupils with the knowledge and skills to engage in civic activities and influence decision-making. This unit is timely as it empowers pupils to understand how they can have a voice, exercise their rights and responsibilities, and the impact they can have on their communities and beyond.""" ;
  curric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils know about the role of active citizens.
Pupils know about the functions of local democracy.
Pupils know about the importance of participation and listening to the opinions of others.""" ;
  curric:id "3372"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.718478Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf natcurric:scheme-citizenship-key-stage-3 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-active-citizenship-making-a-positive-difference .

